The English translation of the given German sentence is: "Why America cannot re-elect President Bush"
I have never been particularly politically engaged partisanship-wise, but these are not normal times.
President George W. Bush endangers the security of the United States and the world while simultaneously undermining American values.
Due to my opposition to him, I was demonized by Bush's campaign team.
President Bush entered the 2000 election with a platform that promised an outward policy of "modesty."
If he is re-elected, this will be a vote for the Bush doctrine of preventive war - and the invasion of Iraq - and the world will have to live with the consequences.
By rejecting Bush's policy at the ballot box, America has a chance to regain the world's respect and support.
The terrorist attacks on September 11, 2001, required a strong response.
However, it has also led to the undermining of the comprehensive and honest discussion of pending problems that is so indispensable for democracy - the critical process that democracy cannot do without.
Bush silenced the criticism by declaring it unpatriotic.
For the duration of 18 months following September 11, he managed to suppress any dissent.
In this way, he has led America in the wrong direction.
In fact, Bush played directly into the hands of Osama bin Laden.
The invasion of Afghanistan - where Bin Laden lived and Al Qaeda maintained its training camps - was justified.
The invasion of Iraq was not it.
He was Bush's unintended gift to bin Laden.
Immediately following September 11, spontaneous expressions of sympathy for America occurred all over the world.
This has retreated from widespread bitterness.
More people are willing to risk their lives today to kill Americans than on September 11th.
Bush likes to claim that the terrorists hate Americans for who they are - a freedom-loving people - and not for what they do.
However, war and occupation bring forth innocent victims.
We Americans count our fallen soldiers - more than 1,000 in Iraq.
The rest of the world counts even the Iraqis killed every day - perhaps twenty times as many.
Neither was the torture of inmates at Abu Ghraib prison the work of a few "rotten apples."
She was part of a system for dealing with detainees that was set up by Defense Secretary Donald Rumsfeld.
The world public opinion condemns America, and our troops in Iraq are paying the price for it.
Bush convinced the people that America's security was in good hands with him, by addressing the fears aroused by the September 11 attacks.
In times of danger, people gather around their flag, and Bush took advantage of this by fostering a sense of threat.
His campaign assumes that people ultimately do not care about the truth and will almost believe anything if it is repeated often enough.
There must be something amiss with America if we fall for it.
For example, still about 40% of all Americans believe that Saddam Hussein was somehow involved in the September 11th attacks, despite the fact that the 9/11 Commission - appointed by Bush and chaired by a Republican - conclusively determined that no such connection existed.
One wants to scream: "Wake up, America."
Don't you realize that we are being led by the nose?
The war in Iraq was based on false premises from start to finish - if it ends.
It was a war of its own decision, not out of necessity.
Moreover, America was dragged into war under a pretext: mass destruction weapons could not be found, and the connection to Al Qaeda could not be proven.
Then Bush claimed that America had entered the war to liberate Iraq.
But democracy cannot be imposed on anyone by force.
Saddam Hussein was a tyrant, and the Iraqis - and the world - can be glad that he is gone.
But America had the duty to ensure justice and order; instead, we watched idly as Baghdad and other cities were looted.
If it had really been about the Iraqi people, we would have had to provide a larger number of soldiers for occupation.
We not only had to protect the Ministry of Oil, but also other ministries, museums, and hospitals.
Worse still: Where American soldiers encountered resistance, they employed methods – such as entering private homes and mistreating detainees – that shocked the population, humiliated them, and thereby fostered bitterness and anger.
The retractions and missteps of the Bush Administration are legion.
First, the Iraqi army was dissolved, then America tried to rebuild it.
At first, the USA tried to eliminate the Baathists, then America sought their help.
When the uprisings could no longer be managed, America installed an Iraqi government.
The man who was chosen as your guide was a protege of the CIA with the reputation of a "strong man" - far from being a democratic decision.
Despite Bush's campaign team's efforts to spin the situation, the conditions in Iraq remain bleak.
A large part of the western provincial portion was left to the insurgents. The prospects for the conduct of free and fair elections in January are rapidly diminishing.
Civil war threatens.
Bush's war in Iraq also inflicted incalculable damage on America, weakened its military might, and undermined the morale of the troops.
Before the war, America could project an image of overwhelming strength.
The English translation of "Heute nicht mehr." is "Not anymore today." or more idiomatically, "Not today."
The sentence "Afghanistan entgleitet der Kontrolle" translates to English as:  "Afghanistan is slipping out of control."
North Korea, Iran, Pakistan, and other countries are pursuing nuclear programs with renewed energy.
One can criticize the Bush Administration on many other political issues, but none of them is as significant as Iraq.
The costs of the war amount to nearly 200 billion dollars so far and will continue to rise, as the invasion of Iraq was much easier than the withdrawal will be.
Bush teased John Kerry, asking him to explain what he would do differently.
Kerry responded that he would have done everything differently and that he would be in a better position to free us from our entanglement.
But it will not be easy for him either, for America is mired in a swamp.
Leading military experts and diplomats had desperately warned Bush not to invade Iraq.
He ignored her.
He suppressed the critical process with the argument that any criticism of the supreme commander would endanger the US troops.
But this is Bush's war, and he should be held accountable for it.
The Americans should pause for a moment and ask themselves: Whom do we owe this mess to?
A moment of reflection might raise another question: Does Bush's cowboy behavior qualify him to remain America's commander in chief?
